Assume a closed circuit $\gamma$, with stationary current $I$. On this region, there is a magnetic field $\mathbf B(\mathbf r)$. The force over an element of circuit $d\mathbf l$ is, by Lorentz force:
$$
d\mathbf F = dq\mathbf v\times\mathbf B
$$

Assuming $n$ charge carriers per unit volume of the conductor, where $A$ is the sectional area of the circuit is $A$, the force then becomes:
$$
d\mathbf F = NAq|d\mathbf l|\mathbf v\times\mathbf B = 
NAq|\mathbf v| d\mathbf l\times\mathbf B = 
A|\mathbf J| d\mathbf l\times\mathbf B = 
I d\mathbf l\times\mathbf B
$$

The torque:
$$
d\tau = \mathbf r\times d\mathbf F = 
\mathbf r\times (I d\mathbf l\times\mathbf B) = 
I\mathbf r\times (d\mathbf l\times\mathbf B)
$$

About the torque, notice that if we integrate component by component, we will arrive in: $\tau = I\mathbf A\times\mathbf B$, where $\mathbf A$ is the vector where $A_i$ is the area over of the projections of the curve $\gamma$ over plane xy, yz, zx. At this point, we can find its magnetic moment:
$$
\mathbf m = I\mathbf A = \frac{1}{2}\oint_\gamma \mathbf r\times d\mathbf l
$$

Therefore, the torque can be calculated using magnetic moment:
$$
\tau = \oint_\gamma I\mathbf r\times (d\mathbf l\times\mathbf B) = 
\mathbf m\times\mathbf B
$$

Its possible to prove that such integral also gives vector $\mathbf A$. So, with this we notice it appeared the magnetic moment vector $\mathbf m$, and that we can find the torque easily using it. It coincides with the actual defined value of the magnetic moment vector from the multipole expansion of the magnetic vector potential from localized current distributions. Furthermore, it indicates systems with magnetic moment (such as, magnets) are equivalent to circuit current loops. A similar treatment is possible with general localized current distribution $\mathbf J(\mathbf r)$ instead of a closed current circuit $\gamma$ with statioanry current $I$.

Taylor expansion of the magnetic field gives: $\mathbf B(\mathbf r) = \mathbf B_0 + \mathbf r\cdot\nabla\mathbf B$, until second order. You can consider the gradient of a vector field as the Jacobian matrix of the field. Notice that, we can use such approximation to compute the force over the circuit:
$$
\mathbf F = 
\oint_\gamma Id\mathbf l\times\mathbf B = 
\oint_\gamma Id\mathbf l\times\mathbf B_0 +  \oint_\gamma Id\mathbf l\times\mathbf r\cdot\nabla\mathbf B
$$

The first integral, $\mathbf B_0$ is constant, and will get out the integral. If $I$ is constant, it will also get out, and we will be left with a closed integral over $d\mathbf l$ which is zero. So, the force contribution comes from the non-uniformity of the magnetic field, ie, its second order term expansion:
$$
\mathbf F = 
I\oint_\gamma d\mathbf l\times(\mathbf r\cdot\nabla\mathbf B) = 
(\mathbf m\times\nabla)\times\mathbf B
$$

Done. Here we made use of the magnetic moment. This means, the magnetic moment of experiences a force from an external non-uniform magnetic field (such as, the magnetic field generated by other magnetic dipole). We can simplify:
$$
\mathbf F = 
$$
